271 /// The domain of monotonicity. Monotonicity checking is a 2-ary function that
272 /// recieves a function F and a domain D, and returns whether F is monotonic
273 /// over D.
274 ///
275 ///
276 /// Note: Let F be an N-ary function:
277 ///
278 ///   F(i_1, i_2, ..., i_N)
279 ///
280 /// In other words, F is a SCEV defined within N-nested loops. Here, loops are
281 /// numbered from outermost to innermost. That is, the first loop is the
282 /// outermost loop and i_1 is its iteration number. Similarly, the N-th loop is
283 /// the innermost loop and i_N is its iteration number.
284 enum class SCEVMonotonicityDomain {
285   /// [0, BTC_1] x [0, BTC_2] x ... x [0, BTC_N], where BTC_k is the exact
286   /// backedge-taken count of the k-th loop. If either of BTC_k is unknown, the
287   /// entire domain is ill-defined for F.
288   Entire,
289 
290   /// [L_1, U_1] x [L_2, U_2] x ... x [L_N, U_N], where L_k and U_k are the
291   /// natural numbers that satisfy the following conditions:
292   ///
293   ///   If F(c_1, ..., c_N) is "actually executed", then L_k <= c_k <= U_k.
294   ///
295   /// This means that the effective domain is a superset of where F is actually
296   /// executed. Notably, L_k and U_k are not explicitly computed. We only
297   /// require the existence of such L_k and U_k. Also, we do not require L_k and
298   /// U_k to be the tightest bounds.
299   Effective,
300 };
